postcontent:
I have a newer Kel Tec P32 parkerized for sale or trade in good condition. Send me your offer. This is the perfect conceal carry gun. Some hollow point ammo included.

P-32

The P-32 is a semi-automatic, locked breech pistol, chambered for the .32 Auto cartridge.The firing mechanism is double action only. The magazine has a 7 round capacity. The Kel-Tec P-32 is the lightest .32 Auto pistol ever made. Thanks to its locking dynamics and superior ergonometry, perceived recoil and practical accuracy are comparable to much larger guns. The P-32 is mainly intended for plainclothes police officers as a secondary weapon, or for concealed carry by licensed citizens. The small grip size and light trigger pull make the P-32 ideal for female shooters.

TECHNICAL SPECIFICATIONS

Calibers:	                32 AUTO
Weight unloaded:	6.6 oz.	186g
Loaded magazine:	2.8 oz.	81mm
Length:	                5.1"	129mm
Height:	                3.5"	89mm
Width:	                .75"	19mm
Barrel Length:	        2.7"	68mm
Sight radius:	        3.8"	96mm
Muzzle Energy Max:    200ft-lbs	240J
Capacity:	                7 + 1 rounds
Trigger Pull:	        5 lbs	23N

The P-32 has six main component groups: barrel, slide, firing mechanism, grip, and magazine. The barrel is made of SAE 4140 ordnance steel, heat treated to 48 HRC. The slide is also 4140 steel, and contains the firing pin and the extractor. The rectangular frame is machined from solid 7075-T6 aluminum and houses the firing mechanism. The trigger connects via a transfer bar to the hammer. The hammer is driven by a novel free floating extension spring. The light weight firing pin transmits the energy of the hammer to ignite the primer. After firing, the hammer block holds the hammer away from the firing pin, providing a mechanical safety.

title: For Sale:  1942 tula SVT 40 7.62x54R
postcontent:
This AD is for the rifle as pictured complete with one (1) ten (10) round magazine. it is a really nice Tokarev SVT40 chambered in 7.62X54r. This is a great looking and shooting gun made in 1942 that has been thru the post WWII Soviet arsenal refurbishing program.

The gun was made at the Tula Arsenal in 1942 – the receiver bridge has the Tula star arsenal mark and is clearly stamped with the year of manufacture. The irregular box that encompasses these marks indicates the rifle was arsenal rebuilt after WWII likely in the 1950’s or 1960’s. only about 7000 of these guns were imported to the United States before the import ban in 1998 this rifle has the small import markings along the reciver beltline and partialy hidden by the stock........

 A summary of the features on the gun are as followed:

 •Features early style 6 baffle muzzle break and type 1 sling swivels ( free moving ) not cast
 •Complete with proper cleaning rod
 •Plumb colored manganese arsenal refinished bolt and bolt carrier Numbers  match on receiver, stock, bolt, bolt carrier, and trigger guard. However, the numbers on the bolt, carrier and trigger guard are electro-pencil arsenal forced match, while the receiver and stock numbers are stamped
 •10 round detachable magazine
 •AVT 40 hardwood stock

 By far the best feature of this rifle is the AVT 40 stock. The AVT 40 was the select fire version of an SVT 40. Of course the merits of a select fire rifle in 7.62X54r with a 10 round magazine are debatable. But the stresses of war in the Soviet Union at the time brought some really dumb ideas and designs to fruition. As a result, we get the AVT 40 stock made of a true hardwood instead of the arctic birch normally used for standard SVT 40 stock. The AVT 40 stock is heavier, denser, and has a larger cross-sectional area in the wrist and along the receiver. I personally would not buy an SVT 40 without an AVT 40 stock just for the added strength, added heft, and beefier grip for larger hands. The AVT 40 stock can be positively identified by the dual selector cut-outs just behind the trigger, one on each side of the stock (see pics). If the stock has only one selector cut-out, it is a standard arctic birch SVT-40 stock.

The bore on the gun is brite and shiny and the the lands and grooves are crisp sharp and well defined. The adjustable gas system is clean and functioning – it can be adjusted using a small wrench. It is not frozen on one setting due to corrosion like many other SVT40's on the market . The rifle is a strong shooter I have had it since 1990 and it has been a safe queen most of the time Ihave fired about 50 rounds thru it in that time. 

The gun sports about 98% of the arsenal refinish, has nice bluing, a bit thin is some spots, but it is all there. The lacquered finish on the stock is strong about 98% complete, with very minor chipping and flaking near the stock cross bolt and the rear of the receiver above the wrist – hardly noticeable.

Changing times have caused me to reevaluate my gun collection and after much debate, I decided to put this gun up for sale. I feel this is a better than average gun, but the i feel the price is very reasonable concidering the condition the gun is in. I am looking for  cash but will accept partial trade if reasonable... Please be real and serious I have had several flakes and scammers contact me only to lowball me or back out at the last second....that being said, I can ship to your FFL dealer or face to face if your local please text REDACTED  ...
